snippet.textDisplay:
When I was younger I had all my canines removed while I was awake and I couldn't eat tough food right for a year.

Now recently (November) I had 6 teeth removed under sedation, 4 molars and 2 canines that were still in my gum. After the surgery I thought I was like dead or something!?! Like in hell or whatever. But I was just really sad and then the nurse said " Oh you'll be fine, good enough for school on Monday "

On Monday

I felt dead I was in no physical condition to walk as I was extremely dizzy and I still couldn't even eat bread.

I just wanted to share that as its my dentist story.

snippet.textDisplay:
"which made me chew on the left side of my mouth for like a whole year"

My upper teeth on the right side of my mouth never came out on their own, and they instead solidified way up there close to the sinuses. It has gotten to the point where i had to go to the hospital for a surgery to take out a fragment of teeth that wasn't taken out properly the first time.

In an effort to make the teeth go down, the dentists (yes, plural) tried to put an button and rubber band on the ones that hadn't come out, and literally SCREWED A METAL BAR ON MY JAW, which had a hook for the band.

Good news is, it worked. Mostly. Still have one up there right now. And they still need to take out my wisdom teeth.
Edit: Typo

snippet.textDisplay: I have a childhood memory of when in 4th or 5th grade one of my molars started to grow out. Except... the molar that was there originally didn’t come out yet. So it just decided to grow on the side, slanting inwards. I had it for like a few days to like a week, ( i don’t remember specific details ) but i do know that my baby molar came out during band class... And during that class, we were practicing outside, preparing for a parade they do like every year. So while we were doing that it just came out. And since i play the trombone, it was just like sitting inside the mouthpiece. Little blood, but it was just like having any other tooth fall out. Its been about 5 years since then, and i still remember it.
